snOspfRouterId.name: snOspfRouterId
snOspfRouterId.description: A 32-bit integer uniquely identifying the router in the Autonomous System. By convention, to ensure uniqueness, this should default to the value of one of the router's IP interface addresses.

snOspfAdminStat.name: snOspfAdminStat
snOspfAdminStat.description: The administrative status of OSPF in the router. The value 'enabled' denotes that the OSPF Process is active on at least one interface; 'disabled' disables it on all interfaces.

snOspfASBdrRtrStatus.name: snOspfASBdrRtrStatus
snOspfASBdrRtrStatus.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 3.3 Classification of routers
snOspfASBdrRtrStatus.description: A flag to note whether this router is an Autonomous System border router.

snOspfRedisMode.name: snOspfRedisMode
snOspfRedisMode.description: The Redistribution status of OSPF in the router. The value 'enabled' denotes that the OSPF Redistribution is active; 'disabled' disables it on the router.

snOspfDefaultOspfMetricValue.name: snOspfDefaultOspfMetricValue
snOspfDefaultOspfMetricValue.description: The metric of using a default OSPF Metric value on this route.

snOspfExternLSACount.name: snOspfExternLSACount
snOspfExternLSACount.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix A.4.5 AS external link advertisements
snOspfExternLSACount.description: The number of external (LS type 5) link-state advertisements in the link-state database.

snOspfExternLSACksumSum.name: snOspfExternLSACksumSum
snOspfExternLSACksumSum.description: The 32-bit unsigned sum of the LS checksums of the external link-state advertisements contained in the link-state database. This sum can be used to determine if there has been a change in a router's link state database, and to compare the link-state database of two routers.

snOspfOriginateNewLSAs.name: snOspfOriginateNewLSAs
snOspfOriginateNewLSAs.description: The number of new link-state advertisements that have been originated. This number is incremented each time the router originates a new LSA.

snOspfRxNewLSAs.name: snOspfRxNewLSAs
snOspfRxNewLSAs.description: The number of link-state advertisements received determined to be new instantiations. This number does not include newer instantiations of self-originated link-state advertisements.

snOspfOspfRedisMetricType.name: snOspfOspfRedisMetricType
snOspfOspfRedisMetricType.description: type1: For External Type 1 (comparable value) the intra-area and inter-area routes, it is an OSPF metric plus the External Metric. type2: For external Type 2 (non-comparable value) routes, it is the external metric.

snOspfExtLsdbLimit.name: snOspfExtLsdbLimit
snOspfExtLsdbLimit.description: The maximum number of non-default AS- external-LSAs entries that can be stored in the link-state database. If the value is -1, then there is no limit. When the number of non-default AS-external-LSAs in a router's link-state database reaches ospfExtLsdbLimit, the router enters Overflow- State. The router never holds more than ospfExtLsdbLimit non-default AS-external-LSAs in its database. OspfExtLsdbLimit MUST be set identically in all routers attached to the OSPF backbone and/or any regular OSPF area. (i.e., OSPF stub areas and NSSAs are excluded).

snOspfExitOverflowInterval.name: snOspfExitOverflowInterval
snOspfExitOverflowInterval.description: The number of seconds that, after entering OverflowState, a router will attempt to leave OverflowState. This allows the router to again originate non-default AS-external-LSAs. When set to 0, the router will not leave Overflow- State until restarted.

snOspfRfc1583Compatibility.name: snOspfRfc1583Compatibility
snOspfRfc1583Compatibility.description: This allows the ospf routing either compatible with RFC1583 or RFC2178. enabled(1)........activate RFC1583 compatibility rather than RFC2178 disabled(0).......disable RFC1583 compatibility and compatible to RFC2178.

snOspfRouterIdFormat.name: snOspfRouterIdFormat
snOspfRouterIdFormat.description: This object is used to specify whether RouterId is represented as IP Address or an Integer. The values that can be written are: integer(0).....as an integer. ipAddress(1)...as IP Address.

snOspfAreaTable.name: snOspfAreaTable
snOspfAreaTable.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 6 The Area Data Structure
snOspfAreaTable.description: Information describing the configured parameters and cumulative statistics of the router's attached areas.

snOspfAreaEntry.name: snOspfAreaEntry
snOspfAreaEntry.description: Information describing the configured parameters and cumulative statistics of one of the router's attached areas.

snOspfAreaId.name: snOspfAreaId
snOspfAreaId.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.2 Area parameters
snOspfAreaId.description: A 32-bit integer uniquely identifying an area. Area ID 0.0.0.0 is used for the OSPF backbone.

snOspfImportASExtern.name: snOspfImportASExtern
snOspfImportASExtern.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.2 Area parameters
snOspfImportASExtern.description: The area's support for importing AS external link- state advertisements. 0: Stub Area Type 1: Normal Area Type 2: NSSA Area Type

snOspfStubMetric.name: snOspfStubMetric
snOspfStubMetric.description: The metric value applied at the default type of service(ospfMetric). By default, this equals the least metric at the type of service among the interfaces to other areas. This Object exist if only if the value of snOspfAreaSummary is snOspfAreaSummary(2); Otherwise, an SNMP_GET/GET_NEXT attempt of this Object will return NO_SUCH_NAME.

snOspfAreaRowStatus.name: snOspfAreaRowStatus
snOspfAreaRowStatus.description: This object is used to create and delete row in the table and control if they are used. The values that can be written are: delete(3)...deletes the row create(4)...creates a new row modify(5)...modifies an exsisting row If the row exists, then a SET with value of create(4) returns error 'badValue'. Deleted rows go away immediately. The following values can be returned on reads: noSuch(0)...no such row invalid(1)...Setting it to 'invalid' has the effect of rendering it inoperative.. valid(2)....the row exists and is valid

snOspfAreaIdFormat.name: snOspfAreaIdFormat
snOspfAreaIdFormat.description: This object is used to specify whether AreaId is represented as IP Address or an Integer. The values that can be written are: integer(0).....as an integer. ipAddress(1)...as IP Address.

snOspfAreaRangeTable.name: snOspfAreaRangeTable
snOspfAreaRangeTable.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.2 Area parameters
snOspfAreaRangeTable.description: A range if IP addresses specified by an IP address/IP network mask pair. For example, class B address range of X.X.X.X with a network mask of 255.255.0.0 includes all IP addresses from X.X.0.0 to X.X.255.255

snOspfAreaRangeEntry.name: snOspfAreaRangeEntry
snOspfAreaRangeEntry.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.2 Area parameters
snOspfAreaRangeEntry.description: A range if IP addresses specified by an IP address/IP network mask pair. For example, class B address range of X.X.X.X with a network mask of 255.255.0.0 includes all IP addresses from X.X.0.0 to X.X.255.255

snOspfAreaRangeAreaID.name: snOspfAreaRangeAreaID
snOspfAreaRangeAreaID.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.2 Area parameters
snOspfAreaRangeAreaID.description: The Area the Address Range is to be found within.

snOspfAreaRangeNet.name: snOspfAreaRangeNet
snOspfAreaRangeNet.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.2 Area parameters
snOspfAreaRangeNet.description: The IP Address of the Net or Subnet indicated by the range.

snOspfAreaRangeMask.name: snOspfAreaRangeMask
snOspfAreaRangeMask.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.2 Area parameters
snOspfAreaRangeMask.description: The Subnet Mask that pertains to the Net or Subnet.

snOspfAreaRangeRowStatus.name: snOspfAreaRangeRowStatus
snOspfAreaRangeRowStatus.description: This object is used to create and delete row in the table and control if they are used. The values that can be written are: delete(3)...deletes the row create(4)...creates a new row modify(5)...modifies an exsisting row If the row exists, then a SET with value of create(4) returns error 'badValue'. Deleted rows go away immediately. The following values can be returned on reads: noSuch(0)...no such row invalid(1)...Setting it to 'invalid' has the effect of rendering it inoperative.. valid(2)....the row exists and is valid

snOspfAreaRangeAreaIdFormat.name: snOspfAreaRangeAreaIdFormat
snOspfAreaRangeAreaIdFormat.description: This object is used to specify whether AreaId is represented as IP Address or an Integer. The values that can be written are: integer(0).....as an integer. ipAddress(1)...as IP Address.

snOspfIfTable.name: snOspfIfTable
snOspfIfTable.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.3 Router interface parameters
snOspfIfTable.description: The OSPF Interface Table describes the interfaces from the viewpoint of OSPF.

snOspfIfEntry.name: snOspfIfEntry
snOspfIfEntry.description: The OSPF Interface Entry describes one interface from the viewpoint of OSPF.

snOspfIfPort.name: snOspfIfPort
snOspfIfPort.description: The physical router port of this OSPF interface.

snOspfIfAreaId.name: snOspfIfAreaId
snOspfIfAreaId.description: A 32-bit integer uniquely identifying the area to which the interface connects. Area ID 0.0.0.0 is used for the OSPF backbone.

snOspfIfAdminStat.name: snOspfIfAdminStat
snOspfIfAdminStat.description: The OSPF interface's administrative status. The value 'enabled' denotes that neighbor relationships may be formed on the interface, and the interface will be advertised as an internal route to some area. The value 'disabled' denotes that the interface is external to OSPF.

snOspfIfRtrPriority.name: snOspfIfRtrPriority
snOspfIfRtrPriority.description: The priority of this interface. Used in multi-access networks, this field is used in the designated router election algorithm. The value 0 signifies that the router is not eligible to become the designated router on this particular network. In the event of a tie in this value, routers will use their router id as a tie breaker.

snOspfIfTransitDelay.name: snOspfIfTransitDelay
snOspfIfTransitDelay.description: The estimated number of seconds it takes to transmit a link- state update packet over this interface.

snOspfIfRetransInterval.name: snOspfIfRetransInterval
snOspfIfRetransInterval.description: The number of seconds between link-state advertisement retransmissions, for adjacencies belonging to this interface. This value is also used when retransmitting database description and link-state request packets.

snOspfIfHelloInterval.name: snOspfIfHelloInterval
snOspfIfHelloInterval.description: The length of time, in seconds, between the Hello packets that the router sends on the interface. This value must be the same for all routers attached to a common network.

snOspfIfRtrDeadInterval.name: snOspfIfRtrDeadInterval
snOspfIfRtrDeadInterval.description: The number of seconds that a router's Hello packets have not been seen before it's neighbors declare the router down. This should be some multiple of the Hello interval. This value must be the same for all routers attached to a common network.

snOspfIfAuthType.name: snOspfIfAuthType
snOspfIfAuthType.description: The authentication type specified for an interface. Additional authentication types may be assigned locally on a per interface basis.

snOspfIfAuthKey.name: snOspfIfAuthKey
snOspfIfAuthKey.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 9 The Interface Data Structure
snOspfIfAuthKey.description: The Authentication Key. If the Area's Authorization Type is simplePassword, and the key length is shorter than 8 octets, the agent will left adjust and zero fill to 8 octets. When read, snOspfIfAuthKey always returns an Octet String of length zero.

snOspfIfMetricValue.name: snOspfIfMetricValue
snOspfIfMetricValue.description: The metric of using this type of service on this interface. The default value of the TOS 0 Metric is 10^8 / ifSpeed.

snOspfIfRowStatus.name: snOspfIfRowStatus
snOspfIfRowStatus.description: This object is used to create and delete row in the table and control if they are used. The values that can be written are: delete(3)...deletes the row create(4)...creates a new row modify(5)...modifies an exsisting row If the row exists, then a SET with value of create(4) returns error 'badValue'. Deleted rows go away immediately. The following values can be returned on reads: noSuch(0)...no such row invalid(1)...Setting it to 'invalid' has the effect of rendering it inoperative.. valid(2)....the row exists and is valid

snOspfIfMd5AuthKeyId.name: snOspfIfMd5AuthKeyId
snOspfIfMd5AuthKeyId.description: The md5 authentication key ID. If the snOspfVirtIfAuthType is set to md5, the value of snOspfIfMd5AuthKeyId must be (1 to 255). This field identifies the algorithm and secret key used to create the message digest appended to the OSPF packet. Key Identifiers are unique per-interface (or equivalently, per-subnet).

snOspfIfMd5AuthKey.name: snOspfIfMd5AuthKey
snOspfIfMd5AuthKey.description: The MD5 Authentication Key. If the Area's Authorization Type is md5, and the key length is shorter than 16 octets, the agent will left adjust and zero fill to 16 octets. When read, snOspfIfMd5AuthKey always returns an Octet String of length zero.

snOspfIfMd5ActivationWaitTime.name: snOspfIfMd5ActivationWaitTime
snOspfIfMd5ActivationWaitTime.description: The md5 authentication key activation wait time is specified in second and the maximum wait time is 14400 seconds (4 hours).

snOspfIfAreaIdFormat.name: snOspfIfAreaIdFormat
snOspfIfAreaIdFormat.description: This object is used to specify whether AreaId is represented as IP Address or an Integer. The values that can be written are: integer(0).....as an integer. ipAddress(1)...as IP Address.

snOspfIfPassiveMode.name: snOspfIfPassiveMode
snOspfIfPassiveMode.description: This object control the passive mode of this interface.

snOspfIfDatabaseFilterAllOut.name: snOspfIfDatabaseFilterAllOut
snOspfIfDatabaseFilterAllOut.description: This object control the filtering of outgoing OSPF LSA on this interface.

snOspfIfMtuIgnore.name: snOspfIfMtuIgnore
snOspfIfMtuIgnore.description: This object control MTU detection mode of this interface.

snOspfIfNetworkP2mp.name: snOspfIfNetworkP2mp
snOspfIfNetworkP2mp.description: This object enable/disable P2MP mode of this interface.

snOspfIf2AreaIdFormat.description: This object is used to specify whether AreaId is represented as IP Address or an Integer. The values that can be written are: integer(0).....as an integer. ipAddress(1)...as IP Address.

snOspfVirtIfEntry.description: Information about a single Virtual Interface.

snOspfVirtIfAreaID.name: snOspfVirtIfAreaID
snOspfVirtIfAreaID.description: The Transit Area that the Virtual Link traverses. By definition, this is not 0.0.0.0

snOspfVirtIfNeighbor.name: snOspfVirtIfNeighbor
snOspfVirtIfNeighbor.description: The Router ID of the Virtual Neighbor.

snOspfVirtIfTransitDelay.name: snOspfVirtIfTransitDelay
snOspfVirtIfTransitDelay.description: The estimated number of seconds it takes to transmit a link- state update packet over this interface.

snOspfVirtIfRetransInterval.name: snOspfVirtIfRetransInterval
snOspfVirtIfRetransInterval.description: The number of seconds between link-state advertisement retransmissions, for adjacencies belonging to this interface. This value is also used when retransmitting database description and link-state request packets. This value should be well over the expected round-trip time.

snOspfVirtIfHelloInterval.name: snOspfVirtIfHelloInterval
snOspfVirtIfHelloInterval.description: The length of time, in seconds, between the Hello packets that the router sends on the interface. This value must be the same for the virtual neighbor.

snOspfVirtIfAuthKey.name: snOspfVirtIfAuthKey
snOspfVirtIfAuthKey.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 9 The Interface Data Structure
snOspfVirtIfAuthKey.description: If Authentication Type is simplePassword, the device will left adjust and zero fill to 8 octets. When read, snOspfVifAuthKey always returns a string of length zero.

snOspfRedisTable.name: snOspfRedisTable
snOspfRedisTable.description: The OSPF Redistribution Table contains a list of routes that could be imported into the OSPF domain.

snOspfRedisEntry.name: snOspfRedisEntry
snOspfRedisEntry.description: The OSPF Redistribution Entry specifies a particular RIP or Static route to be imported into the OSPF domain.

snOspfRedisIndex.name: snOspfRedisIndex
snOspfRedisIndex.description: The destination IP address that associates with this particular route.

snOspfRedisIpAddress.name: snOspfRedisIpAddress
snOspfRedisIpAddress.description: The destination IP address that associates with this particular route.

snOspfRedisMask.name: snOspfRedisMask
snOspfRedisMask.description: The Subnet Mask that pertains to this route.

snOspfRedisAction.name: snOspfRedisAction
snOspfRedisAction.description: The action to be taken if the route match this entry. noImport(0): - the route is NOT imported into OSPF Domain. import(1): - the route is imported into OSPF Domain as external type 2 route.

snOspfRedisProtocol.name: snOspfRedisProtocol
snOspfRedisProtocol.description: The imported routes into OSPF domain is set in the following: rip(1): - the RIP route. all(2): - all protocol route. static(3): - the static route. bgp(4): - the BGP route. connected(5): - the connected route. isis(6): - the ISIS route.

snOspfRedisSetOspfMetric.name: snOspfRedisSetOspfMetric
snOspfRedisSetOspfMetric.description: The value indicates to which the route metric should match: disabled(0): - the route metric does NOT match the OSPF metric field. enabled(1): - the route metric matches the OSPF metric field.

snOspfRedisOspfMetricValue.name: snOspfRedisOspfMetricValue
snOspfRedisOspfMetricValue.description: The metric of using OSPF Metric value on this route.

snOspfRedisMatchRipMetric.name: snOspfRedisMatchRipMetric
snOspfRedisMatchRipMetric.description: The value indicates to which the route metric should match: disabled(0): - the route metric does NOT match the RIP metric field. enabled(1): - the route metric matches the RIP metric field.

snOspfRedisRipMetricValue.name: snOspfRedisRipMetricValue
snOspfRedisRipMetricValue.description: The metric of using RIP Metric value (1 to 15 hops) on this route.

snOspfNbrTable.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 10 The Neighbor Data Structure
snOspfNbrTable.description: A table of non-virtual neighbor information.

snOspfNbrEntry.name: snOspfNbrEntry
snOspfNbrEntry.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 10 The Neighbor Data Structure
snOspfNbrEntry.description: The information regarding a single neighbor.

snOspfNbrEntryIndex.name: snOspfNbrEntryIndex
snOspfNbrEntryIndex.description: The table entry index of this neighbor.

snOspfNbrPort.name: snOspfNbrPort
snOspfNbrPort.description: The physical port of this neighbor.

snOspfNbrIpAddr.name: snOspfNbrIpAddr
snOspfNbrIpAddr.description: The IP address of this neighbor.

snOspfNbrIndex.name: snOspfNbrIndex
snOspfNbrIndex.description: The neighbor index of each port and each IP address.

snOspfNbrRtrId.name: snOspfNbrRtrId
snOspfNbrRtrId.description: A 32-bit integer (represented as a type IpAddress) uniquely identifying the neighboring router in the Autonomous System.

snOspfNbrOptions.name: snOspfNbrOptions
snOspfNbrOptions.description: A Bit Mask corresponding to the neighbor's op- tions field. Bit 0, if set, indicates that the system will operate on Type of Service metrics other than TOS 0. If zero, the neighbor will ignore all metrics except the TOS 0 metric. Bit 1, if set, indicates that the associated area accepts and operates on external informa- tion; if zero, it is a stub area. Bit 2, if set, indicates that the system is ca- pable of routing IP Multicast datagrams; i.e., that it implements the Multicast Extensions to OSPF. Bit 3, if set, indicates that the associated area is an NSSA. These areas are capable of carrying type 7 external advertisements, which are translated into type 5 external advertise- ments at NSSA borders.

snOspfNbrPriority.name: snOspfNbrPriority
snOspfNbrPriority.description: The priority of this neighbor in the designat- ed router election algorithm. The value 0 sig- nifies that the neighbor is not eligible to be- come the designated router on this particular network.

snOspfNbrState.name: snOspfNbrState
snOspfNbrState.description: The State of the relationship with this Neigh- bor.

snOspfNbrEvents.name: snOspfNbrEvents
snOspfNbrEvents.description: The number of times this neighbor relationship has changed state, or an error has occurred.

snOspfNbrLsRetransQLen.name: snOspfNbrLsRetransQLen
snOspfNbrLsRetransQLen.description: The current length of the retransmission queue.

snOspfVirtNbrTable.name: snOspfVirtNbrTable
snOspfVirtNbrTable.description: A table of virtual neighbor information.

snOspfVirtNbrEntryIndex.name: snOspfVirtNbrEntryIndex
snOspfVirtNbrEntryIndex.description: The table entry index of this virtual neighbor.

snOspfVirtNbrRtrId.name: snOspfVirtNbrRtrId
snOspfVirtNbrRtrId.description: A 32-bit integer uniquely identifying the neighboring router in the Autonomous System.

snOspfVirtNbrIpAddr.name: snOspfVirtNbrIpAddr
snOspfVirtNbrIpAddr.description: The IP address this Virtual Neighbor is using.

snOspfVirtNbrOptions.name: snOspfVirtNbrOptions
snOspfVirtNbrOptions.description: A bit map corresponding to the neighbor's options field. Thus, Bit 1, if set, indicates that the neighbor supports Type of Service Routing; if zero, no metrics other than TOS 0 are in use by the neighbor.

snOspfVirtNbrState.name: snOspfVirtNbrState
snOspfVirtNbrState.description: The state of the Virtual Neighbor Relationship.

snOspfVirtNbrEvents.name: snOspfVirtNbrEvents
snOspfVirtNbrEvents.description: The number of times this virtual link has changed its state, or an error has occurred.

snOspfVirtNbrLSRetransQLen.name: snOspfVirtNbrLSRetransQLen
snOspfVirtNbrLSRetransQLen.description: The current length of the retransmission queue.

snOspfVirtNbrAreaIdFormat.name: snOspfVirtNbrAreaIdFormat
snOspfVirtNbrAreaIdFormat.description: This object is used to specify whether AreaId is represented as IP Address or an Integer. The values that can be written are: integer(0).....as an integer. ipAddress(1)...as IP Address.

snOspfLsdbTable.name: snOspfLsdbTable
snOspfLsdbTable.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 12 Link State Advertisements
snOspfLsdbTable.description: The OSPF Process's Links State Database.

snOspfLsdbEntryIndex.name: snOspfLsdbEntryIndex
snOspfLsdbEntryIndex.description: The table entry index of this Link State Database.

snOspfLsdbAreaId.name: snOspfLsdbAreaId
snOspfLsdbAreaId.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.2 Area parameters
snOspfLsdbAreaId.description: The 32 bit identifier of the Area from which the LSA was received.

snOspfLsdbType.name: snOspfLsdbType
snOspfLsdbType.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix A.4.1 The Link State Advertisement header
snOspfLsdbType.description: The type of the link state advertisement. Each link state type has a separate advertisement format.

snOspfLsdbLsId.name: snOspfLsdbLsId
snOspfLsdbLsId.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 12.1.4 Link State ID
snOspfLsdbLsId.description: The Link State ID is an LS Type Specific field containing either a Router ID or an IP Address; it identifies the piece of the routing domain that is being described by the advertisement.

snOspfLsdbRouterId.name: snOspfLsdbRouterId
snOspfLsdbRouterId.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.1 Global parameters
snOspfLsdbRouterId.description: The 32 bit number that uniquely identifies the originating router in the Autonomous System.

snOspfLsdbSequence.name: snOspfLsdbSequence
snOspfLsdbSequence.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 12.1.6 LS sequence number
snOspfLsdbSequence.description: The sequence number field is a signed 32-bit integer. It is used to detect old and duplicate link state advertisements. The space of sequence numbers is linearly ordered. The larger the sequence number the more recent the advertisement.

snOspfLsdbAge.name: snOspfLsdbAge
snOspfLsdbAge.description: This field is the age of the link state advertisement in seconds.

snOspfLsdbChecksum.name: snOspfLsdbChecksum
snOspfLsdbChecksum.description: This field is the checksum of the complete contents of the advertisement, excepting the age field. The age field is excepted so that an advertisement's age can be incremented without updating the checksum. The checksum used is the same that is used for ISO connectionless datagrams; it is commonly referred to as the Fletcher checksum.

snOspfLsdbAdvertisement.name: snOspfLsdbAdvertisement
snOspfLsdbAdvertisement.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 12 Link State Advertisements
snOspfLsdbAdvertisement.description: The entire Link State Advertisement, including its header.

snOspfLsdbAreaIdFormat.name: snOspfLsdbAreaIdFormat
snOspfLsdbAreaIdFormat.description: This object is used to specify whether AreaId is represented as IP Address or an Integer. The values that can be written are: integer(0).....as an integer. ipAddress(1)...as IP Address.

snOspfExtLsdbTable.name: snOspfExtLsdbTable
snOspfExtLsdbTable.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 12 Link State Adver- tisements
snOspfExtLsdbTable.description: The OSPF Process's Links State Database.

snOspfExtLsdbEntryIndex.name: snOspfExtLsdbEntryIndex
snOspfExtLsdbEntryIndex.description: The table entry index of this Link State Database.

snOspfExtLsdbType.name: snOspfExtLsdbType
snOspfExtLsdbType.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix A.4.1 The Link State Advertisement header
snOspfExtLsdbType.description: The type of the link state advertisement. Each link state type has a separate advertise- ment format.

snOspfExtLsdbLsId.name: snOspfExtLsdbLsId
snOspfExtLsdbLsId.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 12.1.4 Link State ID
snOspfExtLsdbLsId.description: The Link State ID is an LS Type Specific field containing either a Router ID or an IP Address; it identifies the piece of the routing domain that is being described by the advertisement.

snOspfExtLsdbRouterId.name: snOspfExtLsdbRouterId
snOspfExtLsdbRouterId.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.1 Global parameters
snOspfExtLsdbRouterId.description: The 32 bit number that uniquely identifies the originating router in the Autonomous System.

snOspfExtLsdbSequence.name: snOspfExtLsdbSequence
snOspfExtLsdbSequence.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 12.1.6 LS sequence number
snOspfExtLsdbSequence.description: The sequence number field is a signed 32-bit integer. It is used to detect old and dupli- cate link state advertisements. The space of sequence numbers is linearly ordered. The larger the sequence number the more recent the advertisement.

snOspfExtLsdbAge.name: snOspfExtLsdbAge
snOspfExtLsdbAge.description: This field is the age of the link state adver- tisement in seconds.

snOspfExtLsdbChecksum.name: snOspfExtLsdbChecksum
snOspfExtLsdbChecksum.description: This field is the checksum of the complete contents of the advertisement, excepting the age field. The age field is excepted so that an advertisement's age can be incremented without updating the checksum. The checksum used is the same that is used for ISO connec- tionless datagrams; it is commonly referred to as the Fletcher checksum.

snOspfExtLsdbAdvertisement.name: snOspfExtLsdbAdvertisement
snOspfExtLsdbAdvertisement.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 12 Link State Adver- tisements
snOspfExtLsdbAdvertisement.description: The entire Link State Advertisement, including its header.

snOspfAreaStatusTable.name: snOspfAreaStatusTable
snOspfAreaStatusTable.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 6 The Area Data Structure
snOspfAreaStatusTable.description: Information describing the configured parameters and cumulative statistics of the router's attached areas.

snOspfAreaStatusEntry.name: snOspfAreaStatusEntry
snOspfAreaStatusEntry.description: Information describing the configured parameters and cumulative statistics of one of the router's attached areas.

snOspfAreaStatusEntryIndex.name: snOspfAreaStatusEntryIndex
snOspfAreaStatusEntryIndex.description: The table entry index of this Area.

snOspfAreaStatusAreaId.name: snOspfAreaStatusAreaId
snOspfAreaStatusAreaId.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.2 Area parameters
snOspfAreaStatusAreaId.description: A 32-bit integer uniquely identifying an area. Area ID 0.0.0.0 is used for the OSPF backbone.

snOspfAreaStatusImportASExtern.name: snOspfAreaStatusImportASExtern
snOspfAreaStatusImportASExtern.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.2 Area parameters
snOspfAreaStatusImportASExtern.description: The area's support for importing AS external link- state advertisements.

snOspfAreaStatusStubMetric.name: snOspfAreaStatusStubMetric
snOspfAreaStatusStubMetric.description: The metric value applied at the default type of service(ospfMetric). By default, this equals the least metric at the type of service among the interfaces to other areas. This Object exist if only if the value of snOspfAreaSummary is snOspfAreaSummary(2); Otherwise, an SNMP_GET/GET_NEXT attempt of this Object will return NO_SUCH_NAME.

snOspfAreaStatusSpfRuns.name: snOspfAreaStatusSpfRuns
snOspfAreaStatusSpfRuns.description: The number of times that the intra-area route table has been calculated using this area's link-state database. This is typically done using Dijkstra's algorithm.

snOspfAreaStatusAreaBdrRtrCount.name: snOspfAreaStatusAreaBdrRtrCount
snOspfAreaStatusAreaBdrRtrCount.description: The total number of area border routers reachable within this area. This is initially zero, and is calculated in each SPF Pass.

snOspfAreaStatusASBdrRtrCount.name: snOspfAreaStatusASBdrRtrCount
snOspfAreaStatusASBdrRtrCount.description: The total number of Autonomous System border routers reachable within this area. This is initially zero, and is calculated in each SPF Pass.

snOspfAreaStatusLSACount.name: snOspfAreaStatusLSACount
snOspfAreaStatusLSACount.description: The total number of link-state advertisements in this area's link-state database, excluding AS External LSA's.

snOspfAreaStatusLSACksumSum.name: snOspfAreaStatusLSACksumSum
snOspfAreaStatusLSACksumSum.description: The 32-bit unsigned sum of the link-state advertisements' LS checksums contained in this area's link-state database. This sum excludes external (LS type 5) link-state advertisements. The sum can be used to determine if there has been a change in a router's link state database, and to compare the link-state database of two routers.

snOspfAreaStatusAreaIdFormat.name: snOspfAreaStatusAreaIdFormat
snOspfAreaStatusAreaIdFormat.description: This object is used to specify whether AreaId is represented as IP Address or an Integer. The values that can be written are: integer(0).....as an integer. ipAddress(1)...as IP Address.

snOspfIfStatusTable.name: snOspfIfStatusTable
snOspfIfStatusTable.description: The OSPF Interface Status Table describes the interfaces from the viewpoint of OSPF.

snOspfIfStatusEntry.name: snOspfIfStatusEntry
snOspfIfStatusEntry.description: The OSPF Interface Entry describes one interface from the viewpoint of OSPF.

snOspfIfStatusEntryIndex.name: snOspfIfStatusEntryIndex
snOspfIfStatusEntryIndex.description: The table entry index of this Area.

snOspfIfStatusPort.name: snOspfIfStatusPort
snOspfIfStatusPort.description: The physical router port of this OSPF interface.

snOspfIfStatusIpAddress.name: snOspfIfStatusIpAddress
snOspfIfStatusIpAddress.description: The IP address of this OSPF interface.

snOspfIfStatusAreaId.name: snOspfIfStatusAreaId
snOspfIfStatusAreaId.description: A 32-bit integer uniquely identifying the area to which the interface connects. Area ID 0.0.0.0 is used for the OSPF backbone.

snOspfIfStatusType.name: snOspfIfStatusType
snOspfIfStatusType.description: The OSPF interface type. By way of a default, this field may be intuited from the corresponding value of ifType. Broadcast LANs, such as Ethernet and IEEE 802.5, take the value 'broadcast', X.25, Frame Relay, and similar technologies take the value 'nbma', and links that are definitively point to point take the value 'pointToPoint'.

snOspfIfStatusAdminStat.name: snOspfIfStatusAdminStat
snOspfIfStatusAdminStat.description: The OSPF interface's administrative status. The value 'enabled' denotes that neighbor relationships may be formed on the interface, and the interface will be advertised as an internal route to some area. The value 'disabled' denotes that the interface is external to OSPF.

snOspfIfStatusRtrPriority.name: snOspfIfStatusRtrPriority
snOspfIfStatusRtrPriority.description: The priority of this interface. Used in multi-access networks, this field is used in the designated router election algorithm. The value 0 signifies that the router is not eligible to become the designated router on this particular network. In the event of a tie in this value, routers will use their router id as a tie breaker.

snOspfIfStatusTransitDelay.name: snOspfIfStatusTransitDelay
snOspfIfStatusTransitDelay.description: The estimated number of seconds it takes to transmit a link- state update packet over this interface.

snOspfIfStatusRetransInterval.name: snOspfIfStatusRetransInterval
snOspfIfStatusRetransInterval.description: The number of seconds between link-state advertisement retransmissions, for adjacencies belonging to this interface. This value is also used when retransmitting database description and link-state request packets.

snOspfIfStatusHelloInterval.name: snOspfIfStatusHelloInterval
snOspfIfStatusHelloInterval.description: The length of time, in seconds, between the Hello packets that the router sends on the interface. This value must be the same for all routers attached to a common network.

snOspfIfStatusRtrDeadInterval.name: snOspfIfStatusRtrDeadInterval
snOspfIfStatusRtrDeadInterval.description: The number of seconds that a router's Hello packets have not been seen before it's neighbors declare the router down. This should be some multiple of the Hello interval. This value must be the same for all routers attached to a common network.

snOspfIfStatusDesignatedRouter.name: snOspfIfStatusDesignatedRouter
snOspfIfStatusDesignatedRouter.description: The IP Address of the Designated Router.

snOspfIfStatusBackupDesignatedRouter.name: snOspfIfStatusBackupDesignatedRouter
snOspfIfStatusBackupDesignatedRouter.description: The IP Address of the Backup Designated Router.

snOspfIfStatusEvents.name: snOspfIfStatusEvents
snOspfIfStatusEvents.description: The number of times this OSPF interface has changed its state, or an error has occurred.

snOspfIfStatusAuthType.name: snOspfIfStatusAuthType
snOspfIfStatusAuthType.description: The authentication type specified for an interface. Additional authentication types may be assigned locally on a per interface basis.

snOspfIfStatusAuthKey.name: snOspfIfStatusAuthKey
snOspfIfStatusAuthKey.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 9 The Interface Data Structure
snOspfIfStatusAuthKey.description: The Authentication Key. If the Area's Authorization Type is simplePassword, and the key length is shorter than 8 octets, the agent will left adjust and zero fill to 8 octets. When read, snOspfIfStatusAuthKey always returns an Octet String of length zero.

snOspfIfStatusMetricValue.name: snOspfIfStatusMetricValue
snOspfIfStatusMetricValue.description: The metric of using this type of service on this interface. The default value of the TOS 0 Metric is 10^8 / ifSpeed.

snOspfIfStatusMd5AuthKeyId.name: snOspfIfStatusMd5AuthKeyId
snOspfIfStatusMd5AuthKeyId.description: The md5 authentication key ID. If the snOspfVirtIfAuthType is set to md5, the value of snOspfIfMd5AuthKeyId must be (1 to 255). This field identifies the algorithm and secret key used to create the message digest appended to the OSPF packet. Key Identifiers are unique per-interface (or equivalently, per-subnet).

snOspfIfStatusMd5AuthKey.name: snOspfIfStatusMd5AuthKey
snOspfIfStatusMd5AuthKey.description: The MD5 Authentication Key. If the Area's Authorization Type is md5, and the key length is shorter than 16 octets, the agent will left adjust and zero fill to 16 octets. When read, snOspfIfMd5AuthKey always returns an Octet String of length zero.

snOspfIfStatusMd5ActivationWaitTime.name: snOspfIfStatusMd5ActivationWaitTime
snOspfIfStatusMd5ActivationWaitTime.description: The md5 authentication key activation wait time is specified in second and the maximum wait time is 14400 seconds (4 hours).

snOspfIfStatusAreaIdFormat.name: snOspfIfStatusAreaIdFormat
snOspfIfStatusAreaIdFormat.description: This object is used to specify whether AreaId is represented as IP Address or an Integer. The values that can be written are: integer(0).....as an integer. ipAddress(1)...as IP Address.

snOspfVirtIfStatusTable.name: snOspfVirtIfStatusTable
snOspfVirtIfStatusTable.reference: OSPF Version 2, Appendix C.4 Virtual link parameters
snOspfVirtIfStatusTable.description: Information about this router's virtual interfaces.

snOspfVirtIfStatusEntry.name: snOspfVirtIfStatusEntry
snOspfVirtIfStatusEntry.description: Information about a single Virtual Interface.

snOspfVirtIfStatusEntryIndex.name: snOspfVirtIfStatusEntryIndex
snOspfVirtIfStatusEntryIndex.description: The table entry index of this Area.

snOspfVirtIfStatusAreaID.name: snOspfVirtIfStatusAreaID
snOspfVirtIfStatusAreaID.description: The Transit Area that the Virtual Link traverses. By definition, this is not 0.0.0.0

snOspfVirtIfStatusNeighbor.name: snOspfVirtIfStatusNeighbor
snOspfVirtIfStatusNeighbor.description: The Router ID of the Virtual Neighbor.

snOspfVirtIfStatusTransitDelay.name: snOspfVirtIfStatusTransitDelay
snOspfVirtIfStatusTransitDelay.description: The estimated number of seconds it takes to transmit a link- state update packet over this interface.

snOspfVirtIfStatusRetransInterval.name: snOspfVirtIfStatusRetransInterval
snOspfVirtIfStatusRetransInterval.description: The number of seconds between link-state advertisement retransmissions, for adjacencies belonging to this interface. This value is also used when retransmitting database description and link-state request packets. This value should be well over the expected round-trip time.

snOspfVirtIfStatusHelloInterval.name: snOspfVirtIfStatusHelloInterval
snOspfVirtIfStatusHelloInterval.description: The length of time, in seconds, between the Hello packets that the router sends on the interface. This value must be the same for the virtual neighbor.

snOspfVirtIfStatusRtrDeadInterval.name: snOspfVirtIfStatusRtrDeadInterval
snOspfVirtIfStatusRtrDeadInterval.description: The number of seconds that a router's Hello packets have not been seen before it's neighbors declare the router down. This should be some multiple of the Hello interval. This value must be the same for the virtual neighbor.

snOspfVirtIfStatusEvents.name: snOspfVirtIfStatusEvents
snOspfVirtIfStatusEvents.description: The number of state changes or error events on this Virtual Link.

snOspfVirtIfStatusAuthType.name: snOspfVirtIfStatusAuthType
snOspfVirtIfStatusAuthType.description: The authentication type specified for an interface. Additional authentication types may be assigned locally on a per interface basis.

snOspfVirtIfStatusAuthKey.name: snOspfVirtIfStatusAuthKey
snOspfVirtIfStatusAuthKey.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 9 The Interface Data Structure
snOspfVirtIfStatusAuthKey.description: If Authentication Type is simplePassword, the device will left adjust and zero fill to 8 octets. When read, snOspfVifAuthKey always returns a string of length zero.

snOspfVirtIfStatusMd5AuthKeyId.name: snOspfVirtIfStatusMd5AuthKeyId
snOspfVirtIfStatusMd5AuthKeyId.description: The md5 authentication key ID. If the snOspfVirtIfAuthType is set to md5, the value of snOspfVirtIfMd5AuthKeyId must be (1 to 255). This field identifies the algorithm and secret key used to create the message digest appended to the OSPF packet. Key Identifiers are unique per-interface (or equivalently, per-subnet).

snOspfVirtIfStatusMd5AuthKey.name: snOspfVirtIfStatusMd5AuthKey
snOspfVirtIfStatusMd5AuthKey.reference: OSPF Version 2, Section 9 The Interface Data Structure
snOspfVirtIfStatusMd5AuthKey.description: The MD5 Authentication Key. If the Area's Authorization Type is md5, and the key length is shorter than 16 octets, the agent will left adjust and zero fill to 16 octets. When read, snOspfIfMd5AuthKey always returns an Octet String of length zero.

snOspfVirtIfStatusMd5ActivationWaitTime.name: snOspfVirtIfStatusMd5ActivationWaitTime
snOspfVirtIfStatusMd5ActivationWaitTime.description: The md5 authentication key activation wait time is specified in second and the maximum wait time is 14400 seconds (4 hours).

snOspfVirtIfStatusAreaIdFormat.name: snOspfVirtIfStatusAreaIdFormat
snOspfVirtIfStatusAreaIdFormat.description: This object is used to specify whether AreaId is represented as IP Address or an Integer. The values that can be written are: integer(0).....as an integer. ipAddress(1)...as IP Address.

snOspfRoutingInfoTable.name: snOspfRoutingInfoTable
snOspfRoutingInfoTable.description: Information about this router's routing information.

snOspfRoutingInfoEntry.name: snOspfRoutingInfoEntry
snOspfRoutingInfoEntry.description: Information about a single ABR/ASBR Routing entry.

snOspfRoutingInfoIndex.name: snOspfRoutingInfoIndex
snOspfRoutingInfoIndex.description: The table entry index of this Routing entry.

snOspfRoutingInfoRouterID.name: snOspfRoutingInfoRouterID
snOspfRoutingInfoRouterID.description: The Router ID of the destination router.

snOspfRoutingInfoRouterType.name: snOspfRoutingInfoRouterType
snOspfRoutingInfoRouterType.description: The Router type of the destination router as the following: abr (1) -- area border router. asbr (2) -- autonomous sytem border router. abrANDasbr(3) -- area border and autonomous system border router.

snOspfRoutingInfoNextHopRouterID.name: snOspfRoutingInfoNextHopRouterID
snOspfRoutingInfoNextHopRouterID.description: The router ID of the next hop destination router.

snOspfRoutingInfoOutgoingInterface.name: snOspfRoutingInfoOutgoingInterface
snOspfRoutingInfoOutgoingInterface.description: The outgoing interface of the destination router.

snOspfSetTrap.name: snOspfSetTrap
snOspfSetTrap.description: A four-octet string serving as a bit map for the trap events defined by the OSPF traps. This object is used to enable and disable specific OSPF traps where a 1 in the bit field represents enabled. The right-most bit (least significant) represents trap 0.

snOspfConfigErrorType.name: snOspfConfigErrorType
snOspfConfigErrorType.description: Potential types of configuration conflicts. Used by the ospfConfigError and ospfConfigVir- tError traps.

snOspfPacketSrc.name: snOspfPacketSrc
snOspfPacketSrc.description: The IP address of an inbound packet that can- not be identified by a neighbor instance.

snOspfTrapsGenerationMode.name: snOspfTrapsGenerationMode
snOspfTrapsGenerationMode.description: Indicates if the generation of any OSPF traps is permitted on the router. The value 'enabled' denotes that the OSPF Traps can be generated by the router; 'disabled' denotes that the OSPF Traps can not be generated by the router even when snOspfSetTrap indicates the generation of specific OSPF Traps. This object provides global control on the generation of ospf traps.
